PK, OAuth ka transcript bahut lamba hai isliye confusing lagta hai. Main OAuth 2.0 ko simple mental model + real example se explain karta hoon taaki feel aaye system design ka.

1️⃣ OAuth 2.0 kya hai?

OAuth ka full form:

Open Authorization

Purpose:

Third-party apps ko limited access dena
without sharing password

Example:

Login with Google
Login with GitHub
Login with Facebook

Tum password Google ko hi dete ho, Instagram ko nahi.

2️⃣ Real Example

Scenario:

User → Instagram login
Option → Login with Google

Flow:

User → Instagram
Instagram → Google
Google → Verify user
Google → Send token
Instagram → Fetch user info
3️⃣ OAuth Actors (4 Roles)

OAuth me 4 components hote hain.

1️⃣ Resource Owner

User.

Example:

You (Gmail account holder)
2️⃣ Client

Application jo data use karna chahta hai.

Example:

Instagram
3️⃣ Authorization Server

Server jo permission verify karta hai.

Example:

accounts.google.com
4️⃣ Resource Server

Server jahan actual data stored hai.

Example:

Google API server
Visual
User
 │
 │ login
 ▼
Client (Instagram)
 │
 │ authorization
 ▼
Authorization Server (Google Auth)
 │
 │ token
 ▼
Resource Server (Google API)
4️⃣ OAuth Authorization Code Flow (Most Important)

Ye most used flow hai.

Steps:

Step 1 — Client Registration

Instagram Google ke OAuth server me register hota hai.

Google deta hai:

client_id
client_secret
Step 2 — User Clicks Login with Google

User click karta hai:

Sign in with Google

Instagram redirect karta hai:

Google Authorization Server
Step 3 — User Authentication

Google user se login karwata hai.

email
password

Aur consent deta hai.

Example:

Instagram wants to access:
email
profile

User:

Allow
Step 4 — Authorization Code

Google redirect karta hai:

instagram.com/callback

Saath me deta hai:

authorization_code

Example:

code=abc123
Step 5 — Exchange Code for Token

Instagram Google ko call karta hai:

POST /token

Send karta hai:

authorization_code
client_id
client_secret

Google return karta hai:

access_token
refresh_token
Step 6 — Access Resource

Instagram Google API call karta hai:

GET /userinfo
Authorization: Bearer access_token

Google return karta hai:

{
"name":"Shreyansh",
"email":"abc@gmail.com"
}

User login ho jata hai.

5️⃣ Access Token vs Refresh Token
Access Token

Short-lived token.

Example:

expires_in = 1 hour

Use:

API access
Refresh Token

Long-lived token.

Use:

new access token generate

Example:

POST /token
grant_type=refresh_token
6️⃣ OAuth Security — State Parameter

State use hota hai:

CSRF attack prevent karne ke liye

Flow:

Client send karta hai:

state=random123

Response me same value aani chahiye.

state=random123

Agar match nahi hua:

reject request
7️⃣ OAuth Grant Types

OAuth me multiple grant types hain.

1️⃣ Authorization Code (Most Used)

Use case:

Web apps
Mobile apps

Secure.

2️⃣ Implicit Grant

Direct token milta hai.

But:

Less secure

Ab mostly deprecated.

3️⃣ Password Grant

Client directly password leta hai.

Example:

username
password

Used in trusted apps.

Not recommended.

4️⃣ Client Credentials

Machine-to-machine communication.

Example:

service → service

No user involved.

5️⃣ Refresh Token Grant

Expired access token ko refresh karta hai.

8️⃣ OAuth Flow Summary
User
 │
 │ login
 ▼
Client (Instagram)
 │
 │ redirect
 ▼
Authorization Server (Google)
 │
 │ authorization_code
 ▼
Client
 │
 │ exchange code
 ▼
Access Token
 │
 │ API request
 ▼
Resource Server
9️⃣ OAuth vs Authentication

OAuth actually:

Authorization

But login systems me use hota hai.

Actual authentication standard hai:

OpenID Connect

OAuth + identity layer.

🔟 Real Companies OAuth Use

Examples:

Google Login
GitHub Login
Facebook Login
Microsoft Login
🧠 System Design Mental Model

OAuth ka main idea:

Never share password
Use tokens instead